title: Activation cross sections of proton-induced nuclear reactions on natural hafnium

x4freetext: Activation cross sections of proton-induced nuclear
reactions on natural hafnium

x4codes.hlp: Institute for Nuclear Research (ATOMKI), Debrecen, Hungary

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Nucl. Instrum. Methods in Physics Res., Sect.B, Vol.269, p.2824 (2011)

x4freetext: 23 MeV and 37 MeV
High purity natural hafnium foils 10 micro-m from
Goodfellow, 99.5%.
Ti monitor foils (10 micro-m) and
Al (100 and 50 micro-m) energy degradation foils.
Two stacks were irradiated
with proton beams of 23 and 37 MeV at 100 nA beam
intensities for 1 h. Targets were irradiated in
Faraday-cup type holder. Measurements started from
90 min after EOB. The beam intensity obtained via
charge collection was corrected with the data from the
monitor reaction.
The energy degradation was initially determined by
calculation using the formulas and tables of Andersen
and Ziegler and corrected on the basis of the measured
monitor reaction excitation function. The best
agreement was found after small corrections on the beam
intensity (+5% with respect to the Faraday cup results)
and on the primary beam energy (+0.4 MeV).
Nuclear data were taken from the NuDat2.5 database.
http://www.nndc.bnl.gov/nudat2, except for 177Ta for
which data were taken from the Lund database,
http://nucleardata.nuclear.lu.se.
Chapter 4
Taking into account the cumulative effects of
possible incident energy variation and thickness of
the different targets, the uncertainty of the energy
of the front foil of a stack is around 0.3 MeV and
increases up to 1.1 MeV for the last foil of the
stacks.
The estimated total uncertainty on the
cross-sections was between 11-21%.
The contributing error components are:
number of target nuclei (5%);
beam current (7%);
detector efficiency (5 -7%);
gamma-ray abundances(1-3%).
statistical and peak fitting (1-18%)
Fitted excitation functions were used for
determination of integral physical yields.
